25|$|Hazaragi, {{spoken by}} the <b>Hazaras</b> in Pakistan, {{is similar to}} Dari. It is spoken {{in parts of the}} Quetta {{district}} of Karachi, Islamabad, and in parts of Ziarat. There are estimated to be 900,000 to 1,000,000 Hazaragi-speakers.|$|E
25|$|The OIC {{has been}} criticised {{for failing to}} discuss the {{treatment}} of ethnic minorities within member countries, such as the oppression of the Kurds in Syria and Turkey, the Ahwaz in Iran, the <b>Hazaras</b> in Afghanistan, the 'Al-Akhdam' in Yemen, or the Berbers in Algeria.|$|E
25|$|Maska is a sub-{{tribe of}} Jaghori tribe of <b>Hazaras</b> in Afghanistan. For long times ago Maska and Babah were twin {{brothers}} {{and according to}} the old myth they were separated by knife. In Afghanistan their ancestral place is Sange-e-Masha in Jaghori District of Ghazni Province.|$|E
